Note: ============================================================================
Note: 66-PROC DISPATCHER API: syscall_<name> wrappers
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These provide the canonical syscall_<name> entries required by the
Note: assembly/syscall.runa dispatcher's 66-proc API surface (see
Note: bootstrap/v0.0.8.5/docs/dev/designs/P2-B-cross-platform-threading-syscalls-design.md
Note: Section "Per-platform syscall inventory" line 197).  They route through
Note: the same syscall_N inline-asm thunks declared above; they are intentionally
Note: thin so the dispatcher contract is uniform across all 18 platforms.

Process called "mips64_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_read(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5000 (SYS_READ).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_read = 5000.
    Note: Returns number of bytes read, 0 at EOF, or negative errno on error
    Note: (n64 returns -errno in $v0 with $a3=1 on the kernel side; the kernel
    Note: ABI shim in syscall_N converts to a Linux-style signed return).
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_READ(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_write(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5001 (SYS_WRITE).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_write = 5001.
    Note: Returns number of bytes written or negative errno on error.
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_WRITE(), fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_open(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5002 (SYS_OPEN).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_open = 5002.
    Note: MIPS64 still exposes a legacy mips64_open(2) syscall (unlike arm64/riscv which
    Note: removed it in favour of openat-only).  Returns new file descriptor or
    Note: negative errno on error.
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_OPEN(), filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_close(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5003 (SYS_CLOSE).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_close = 5003.
    Note: Returns 0 on success or negative errno on error.
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_CLOSE(), fd)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_exit(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5058 (SYS_EXIT).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_exit = 5058.
    Note: Terminates the current thread only.  Returns nothing on success
    Note: (process is gone) but the API returns -1 / -errno on failure
    Note: (e.g. kernel rejects an unmappable status value).
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_EXIT(), status)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_brk(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5012 (SYS_BRK).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_brk = 5012.
    Note: Adjusts the program break (end of the data segment).  Returns the
    Note: new break (which may differ from the requested addr if the kernel
    Note: caps it) or -ENOMEM (negative) on failure.
    Return mips64_syscall_1(mips64_SYS_BRK(), addr)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_mmap(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5009 (SYS_MMAP).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_mmap = 5009.
    Note: MIPS64 uses mmap (not mmap2) because n64 has full 64-bit registers
    Note: for the offset argument; no page-shift conversion needed (unlike o32).
    Note: Returns the mapped address (positive) or -errno (negative) on failure.
    Note: n64 has 6 argument registers ($a0-$a5), so all 6 mmap args fit.
    Return mips64_syscall_6(mips64_SYS_MMAP(), addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_munmap(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5011 (SYS_MUNMAP).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_munmap = 5011.
    Note: Unmaps the page-aligned region [addr, addr+length).  Returns 0 on
    Note: success or -EINVAL/-errno (negative) on failure.
    Return mips64_syscall_2(mips64_SYS_MUNMAP(), addr, length)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: mips64_fstat(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5005 (SYS_FSTAT).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_fstat = 5005.
    Note: Writes the struct stat for the given fd into statbuf.  The MIPS64
    Note: stat layout is the n64 ABI variant (64-bit time fields, 64-bit ino).
    Note: Returns 0 on success or -errno on failure.
    Return mips64_syscall_2(mips64_SYS_FSTAT(), fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "mips64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: lseek(2) on MIPS64 n64: syscall number 5008 (SYS_LSEEK).
    Note: Source: Linux kernel arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h __NR_lseek = 5008.
    Note: Repositions the file offset of fd.  Returns the new absolute offset
    Note: from the beginning of the file or -errno on failure.  n64 native
    Note: 64-bit registers cover the full off_t range without _llseek tricks.
    Return mips64_syscall_3(mips64_SYS_LSEEK(), fd, offset, whence)
End Process
